<h2 id="what-not-to-do">7. What NOT to Do in a Crypto Bear Market</h2>

<p>When everyone is losing money, the best trades are often the ones you <em>don't</em> take. Here are the most common bear market mistakes:</p>

<div class="risk-box">
    <strong>&#x26A0;&#xFE0F; The 7 Deadly Bear Market Sins:</strong>
</div>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Panic selling at the bottom.</strong> This is the #1 wealth destroyer. If you survived the drop to -70%, don't sell at -75%. You've already taken the pain. The recovery will come ” but only if you're still holding.</li>
    <li><strong>Using leverage to "average down."</strong> Adding leverage during a bear market is like trying to put out a fire with gasoline. One more leg down and you're liquidated ” zero, gone, finished.</li>
    <li><strong>Chaining into lower-quality assets.</strong> As blue chips drop, some investors sell them to buy "cheaper" meme coins at a "discount." This is almost always a mistake. The best assets recover first and strongest.</li>
    <li><strong>Trying to short the market.</strong> Shorting in crypto is notoriously difficult. Bear market rallies can be 30-100% and will liquidate your shorts before the downtrend resumes. Leave shorts to professional traders.</li>
    <li><strong>FOMO buying dead cat bounces.</strong> After a sharp drop, the market often rallies 20-40% (a "dead cat bounce"). This tricks people into thinking the bottom is in. Then it drops again, even lower.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring DeFi risks.</strong> Do not chase "bear market yield" in unaudited protocols. The 2022 bear market saw multiple DeFi collapses. Stick to blue-chip protocols like Jupiter, Jito, Marinade, and Kamino on Solana.</li>
    <li><strong>Going full nihilist and checking out.</strong> Some people get so frustrated they stop paying attention entirely. This is dangerous ” you need to stay informed so you can act when conditions change. Check prices weekly, stay engaged with the community, and keep learning.</li>
</ol>

